==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈklɪŋ/}}
*: {{rhymes|ɪŋ}}

===Etymology===
Old English? {{term|clingan}} to adhere, to wither; akin to {{etyl|da|en}} {{term|klynge|lang=da}} to cluster, crowd. Compare {{term|clump|lang=en}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# [[fruit|Fruit]] (especially [[peach]]) whose [[flesh]] adheres strongly to the [[pit]].
#* '''1908''', [[w:O. Henry|O. Henry]], ''Hostages to Momus'':
#*: Antelope steaks and fried liver to begin on, and venison cutlets with chili con carne and pineapple fritters, and then some sardines and mixed pickles; and top it off with a can of yellow '''clings''' and a bottle of beer.
# [[adherence]]; [[attachment]]; [[devotion]]
#* Milton
#*: A more tenacious '''cling''' to worldly respects.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|clings|clinging|clung}}

#{{senseid|en|hold tightly}}To [[hold]] very [[tight]]ly, as to not fall off.
#: ''Seaweed '''clung''' to the anchor.''
#* Mrs. Hemans
#*: And what hath life for thee / That thou shouldst '''cling''' to it thus?
# To adhere to an object, without being affixed, in such a way as to follow its contours. Used especially of fabrics and films.
# {{context|transitive}} To cause to adhere to, especially by twining round or embraching.
#* Jonathan Swift
#*: I '''clung''' legs as close to his side as I could.
# {{context|transitive}} To cause to dry up or wither.
#* Shakespeare
#*: If thou speak'st false, / Upon the next tree shalt thou hang alive, / Till famine '''cling''' thee.

